<paper id="1768621358"><title>RSA-type Signatures in the Presence of Transient Faults</title><year>1997</year><authors><author org="University of Louvain;" id="2070444920">Marc Joye</author><author org="University of Louvain;" id="2195205560">Jean-Jacques Quisquater</author><author org="National Univ. of Singapore, Kent Ridge" id="2924724599">Feng Bao</author><author org="National Univ. of Singapore, Kent Ridge" id="2062283694">Robert H. Deng</author></authors><n_citation>33</n_citation><doc_type>Journal</doc_type><references><reference>1515644111</reference><reference>1557014463</reference><reference>1584975026</reference><reference>1595231197</reference><reference>1996360405</reference></references><venue id="106296714" type="J">Lecture Notes in Computer Science</venue><doi>10.1007/BFb0024460</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.50709">Lucas sequence</keyword><keyword weight="0.57211">Cryptography</keyword><keyword weight="0.44374">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.50192">Information protection policy</keyword><keyword weight="0.51036">Communication theory</keyword><keyword weight="0.44361">Algorithm</keyword><keyword weight="0.51005">Elliptic curve</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>In this paper, we show that the presence of transient faults can leak some secret information. We prove that only one faulty RSA-signature is needed to recover one bit of the secret key. Thereafter, we extend this result to Lucas-based and elliptic curve systems.</abstract></paper>